the departmental leads to the department and then into the university as a whole.</div>\n<div class=\"imageCredit\">Rosenberg & Nelson</div>\n<div class=\"imagePermisssions\">Creative Commons</div>\n<div class=\"imageSubmitted\">Jessica&nbsp;Rosenberg\n<div class=\"imageTitle\">Diffusion of Effort</div>\n</div>\n</li><li>\n<a href=\"/por/images/Reports/POR/2025/1821589/1821589_10575020_1738684705720_CCT_diagram--rgov-214x142.png\" original=\"/por/images/Reports/POR/2025/1821589/1821589_10575020_1738684705720_CCT_diagram--rgov-800width.png\" title=\"Communities of Transformation Model\"><img src=\"/por/images/Reports/POR/2025/1821589/1821589_10575020_1738684705720_CCT_diagram--rgov-66x44.png\" alt=\"Communities of Transformation Model\"></a>\n<div class=\"imageCaptionContainer\">\n<div class=\"imageCaption\">The communities of transformation were the mechanism by which the change effort was organized. The diagram shows the interaction between faculty, graduate teaching assistants, and learning assistants (LAs) within and across the targeted course sequences in math, physics, and computer science.</div>\n<div class=\"imageCredit\">Rosenberg & Nelson</div>\n<div class=\"imagePermisssions\">Creative Commons</div>\n<div class=\"imageSubmitted\">Jessica&nbsp;Rosenberg\n<div class=\"imageTitle\">Communities of Transformation Model</div>\n</div>\n</li></ul>\n</div>\n</div></div>\n</div>\n",
  "por_txt_cntn": "\n\nStudies across the STEM disciplines have shown that student engagement and active learning improve student attitudes, retention, and understanding (e.g., Fry, 2014; Freeman et al., 2014; National Research Council, 2012; and references therein), with greater impact on women and previously low-achieving students (Kogan & Laursen, 2014; Laursen et al., 2014). Nevertheless, implementation of these techniques has been limited and often isolated. The goal of this project was to use a faculty-driven grassroots approach to drive change in departmental culture about the use of active and collaborative techniques in the classroom.\r\n\r\n\n\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\n\nIntellectual Merit\r\n\r\n\r\n\n\nThis effort targeted large-enrollment introductory courses with multiple sections and instructors. By using a course-based model rather than an instructor-based model, the project was able to engage with a much larger group of faculty than might have otherwise been involved in a teaching reform effort. Many of the barriers to change we identified were not directly related to the pedagogies used in the classroom but instead were structural. Appropriate classroom space, better communication between instructors in multi-section courses, availability of materials that are tailored for the course and institutional environment, and recognition for teaching-related work all contributed to changing teaching culture and pedagogical choices. For graduate students, robust and ongoing professional development that is aligned with GTAs classroom roles and sensitive to their cultural backgrounds is critical for building their comfort and competence in teaching, particularly as it relates to incorporating pedagogies that were not part of their classroom experiences as students.\r\n\r\n\r\n\n\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\n\nBroader Impacts\r\n\r\n\r\n\n\nThousands of students across many majors at George Mason pass through calculus, calculus-based physics, and introduction to computer science course sequences each year. While a few instructors worked to actively engage students in these courses, the large sizes, lecture-style classrooms, and other structural barriers meant that these efforts were limited to a handful of sections each semester. By focusing on supports needed for sustained change in these courses, this change effort engaged all faculty working with a given course and built materials to support their efforts that were aligned with departmental norms. While the pandemic disrupted some of this work, positive changes were evident. Students reported more active and collaborative learning in their classes, more cooperation and cohesiveness, and a better overall classroom environment. Creating more substantive preparation for graduate teaching assistants as they enter the classroom has improved the experience for the undergraduates while supporting the growth of the next generation of instructors. All of these efforts have been disseminated widely to help others increase the use of active and collaborative pedagogies in their programs.\r\n\t\t\t\t\tLast Modified: 02/04/2025\n\n\t\t\t\t\tSubmitted by: JessicaRosenberg\n"
